Human walking is highly coordinated and optimized for energy efficiency - integrating biomechanical and neuromotor control systems and disruptions to these systems can alter gait mechanics (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20023002/).

Gait speed at midlife was found to be associated with cognitive functioning (https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamanetworkopen/fullarticle/2752818). 
Gait can change in recognizable way due to disturbances in health, with recognizable patterns, such as cautious, stiff-legged and freezing gait (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/lio2.252). Early gait abnormality can be used to help diagnose PD (https://jnnp.bmj.com/content/79/4/368.long, https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25546558/). The type of gait dysfunction can be used to differentiate between different types of dementia (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2574944/#S23). 


gait can be a non invasic early biomarker of health, and quantitative movement could help provide objective characterization of subtle differences in movement.

In gait, quantitative movement analysis can be used for a multitude of purposes. It could be helpful in assessing athletic performance (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12299843/#sec4-sensors-25-04384).
